05231nam a22008535i 9783110777222DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2023939392  a97831107772227 a10.1515/97831107772222doi  a(DE-B1597)613178  a(OCoLC)1402028958  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aHD30.22b.K874 2023 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a338.50246582231 aKupferschmidt, Uri M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Diffusion of “Small” Western Technologies in the Middle East :bInvention, Use and Need in the 19th and 20th Centuries /cUri M. Kupferschmidt. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XII, 278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on Modern Orient ;v4400tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tA note on transliteration -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Who needed department stores in Egypt? -- t2 On the diffusion of “Small” Western technologies and consumer goods in the Middle East -- t3 The social history of the sewing machine in the Middle East -- t4 Leapfrogging from typewriter to personal computer in the Middle East -- t5 From Ibn Haitham to Abou Naddara and Al-Misri Effendi: eyeglasses in the Middle East -- t6 Did the piano have a chance in the Middle East? -- tBibliography -- tList of Figures -- tIndex of proper names -- tIndex of geographical names -- tIndex of subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years we have become interested in the diffusion of “small” Western technologies in the countries of the Middle East during the 19th and 20th centuries, the era of Imperialism and first globalization. We postulated a contrast between “small” and “big” technologies. Under the latter category we may understand railway systems, electricity grids, telegraph networks, and steam navigation, imposed by foreign powers or installed by connected local entrepreneurs. But many “small” Western technologies, such as sewing machines, typewriters, pianos, eyeglasses, and similar consumer goods, which had been developed and manufactured in Europe and America, were wanted, and willingly acquired by the agency of individual users elsewhere. In a few cases, however, the inventions had to be adapted, or were overstepped, and even delayed. Some were adopted as social markers or status symbols only by elites who could afford them. Processes of adoption and diffusion therefore differed according to cultural settings, preferences, and needs. Social and cultural historians, and social scientists, not only of the Middle East, will find in this collection of essays a new approach to the impact of Western technological inventions on the Middle East.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic history. 0aManagerial economics. 4a19. und 20. Jahrhundert. 4aErfindungen. 4aIndustrialisierung. 4aKonsumgüter. 4aNahost. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh  aconsumer goods.  adifferential diffusion.  aglobalization.  aimperial expansion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107773070 cprintz978311077719240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311077722240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110777222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110777222/original